\begin{align*}
x&=\mathbf{m}_{11}x+\mathbf{m}_{12}y\\
y&=\mathbf{m}_{21}x+\mathbf{m}_{22}y;
\end{align*}
where $\mathbf{m}_{ij}$ are the entries of the $2\times2$ matrix $\mathbf{M},$ with $A$ corresponding to $(x,y)$ and $A'$ corresponding to $(x',y').$ By the transformation of coordinates from $(x,y)$ to $(x',y'),$ we know that
\[\begin{pmatrix}x'\\y'\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}a&b\\c&d\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}2\\3\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}3a+2b\\3c+2d\end{pmatrix}.\]
Since $A$ is sent to $A',$ we know that $3a+2b=a$ and $3c+2d=b,$ implying that $a=\boxed{-1},$ $b=\boxed{3},$ $c=\boxed{-\frac25},$ and $d=\boxed{\frac65}.$</think>
