Of complex numbers, the five fifth roots of 1 have the form $e^{2 \pi i n /5}$ for n an integer, and so $z^5 = 1$ is equivalent to $z = e^{2 \pi i n /5}$ for n an integer (not necessarily between 0 and 4). In particular, this is equivalent to $z$ having the form
\begin{align*}\cos{\frac{2 \pi n}{5}} + i \sin{\frac{2 \pi n}{5}}\end{align*}
for an integer $n$. Since rotations take circles to circles, each of $z, z^2, z^3, z^4$ has this form but with different integers $n$; it’s not hard to show that the set of fifth roots of 1, represented as points in the complex plane, should divide the unit circle into five radii evenly so each one can be written in the form
\begin{align*}\cos{\frac{2 \pi N}{5}} + i \sin{\frac{2 \pi N}{5}}\end{align*}
for an integer $N$, and in this way we actually get the five seventh roots of unity for angles $0, 2\pi/5, 4\pi/5, 6\pi/5, 8\pi/5$. \end think
\begin{align*}\cos{\frac{2 \pi N}{5}} + \sin{\frac{2 \pi N}{5}} + \cos{\frac{4 \pi N}{5}} + \sin{\frac{4 \pi N}{5}}\end{align*}
is equal to \begin{align*}\frac{1}{2} \Big{(}1+2 \cos{2 \pi N/5}+2 \cos{4 \pi N/5}\Big{)} = \cos{\frac{6 \pi N}{5}}+\cos{\frac{2 \pi N}{5}} = 2 \cos{\frac{3 \pi N}{5}} \cos{\frac{\pi N}{5}}.\end{align*}
The first and third equalities just come out of the basic formulas for the real part of a complex number and for the square of a complex number.
\end think
\begin{align*}z + \frac{1}{z} + z^2 + \frac{1}{z^2} = a + bi\end{align*} for real numbers $a, b$. We square both sides to get
\begin{align*}\Big{(}a + bi\Big{)} \cdot \Big{(}a - bi\Big{)} = z^2 + \frac{1}{z^2} + z^4 + \frac{1}{z^4},\end{align*}
so
\begin{align*}a^2 + b^2 = 2 + 2 \cos{\frac{4 \pi}{5}}.\end{align*}
Finally, noting that $z^5 = 1$ implies that $z^k \cdot z^{5-k} = 1$ for $k \in \{ 1, 2, 3, 4 \}$, we can see
\begin{align*}a^2 + b^2 = 2 + 2 \cos{\frac{4 \pi}{5}} = 2 + 2 \cos{2 \pi \Big{(}1 - \frac{6 \pi}{5} \Big{)}} = 2 + 2 \cos{2 \pi \frac{6 \pi}{5}} = 4 \cos{2 \pi \frac{3 \pi}{5}} = 4 \cos^2{2 \pi \frac{3 \pi}{10}} = 4 \cos^2{\frac{3 \pi}{5}},\end{align*}
so $a + bi = 2i \cos{\frac{3 \pi}{5}}$, as desired. \end think
