As per the figure, the angle of triangle $\triangle RQS$ at $Q$ is $70^{\circ}$ (Vertical angles). Since $PRT$ is a straight line, the angle at $P$ in $\triangle RPS$ is $110^{\circ}$ and $\angle RPS$ is $70^{\circ}$. By the angle sum property of triangles, the angle at $R$ in $\triangle RPS$ is $40^{\circ}$ ($110^{\circ} + 70^{\circ} = 180^{\circ}$, so $\angle R = 180^{\circ} - 110^{\circ} - 40^{\circ}$). Now, since the angle at $T$ in $\triangle RTS$ is $x$, and we know that $x + x + x = 180^{\circ}$ (the sum of angles in a straight line), we can find $x$.
